Colin,

The general size and restricted areas of the PCB would be manually determined, but the cppn should place most the parts in a way that lends efficient routing of the traces. Cost of the pcb manufacturing process would be directly related to the factor I already identified. Placement (closeness), length of trace, number of thru-holes(factor for cnc), jumpers(another cnc factor), possibly a few more. 

Sent from my iPhone

On Nov 1, 2008, at 3:36 PM, &quot;Colin Green&quot; &lt;colin.green1@...&gt; wrote:

Hi

2008/11/1 kelly parker &lt;bigblockfw@...&gt;:
&gt; Thinking a bit more along the same path (pun intended) would be G code
&gt; optimization.
&gt; I don&#39;t know if you&#39;ve ever watched a cnc mill wander around waisting time
&gt; but it&#39;s expensive
&gt; if you&#39;re mass producing something like PCBs.

This sounds similar to the travelling salesman problem - multiple
points to visit and trying to minimize the overall distance travelled.
So if the layout is already determined you&#39;re probably looking at well
know algorithms for TSP (or TSP like problems). On the other hand the
manufacturing cost of a PCB could be factored into the fitness
function of a layout finding algorithm.

Colin


